04923nam a22006855i 9781400821921DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19981996nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008219217 a10.1515/97814008219212doi  a(DE-B1597)446125  a(OCoLC)979724998  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBJ1474 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a171.81 aMonroe, Kristen Renwick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Heart of Altruism :bPerceptions of a Common Humanity /cKristen Renwick Monroe.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThe Human Face of Altruism -- tAcknowledgments -- tPART I. The Importance of Altruism -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. The Puzzle of Altruism -- tPART II. Narratives: From Self-Interest to Altruism -- tCHAPTER 2. The Entrepreneur -- tCHAPTER 3. The Philanthropist -- tCHAPTER 4. The Heroine -- tCHAPTER 5. Rescuers of Jews in Nazi Europe -- tPART III. Traditional Explanations for Altruism -- tCHAPTER 6. Sociocultural Attributes of Altruism -- tCHAPTER 7. Economic Approaches to Altruism -- tCHAPTER 8. Explanations from Evolutionary Biology -- tCHAPTER 9. Psychological Discussions of Altruism -- tPART IV. The Altruistic Perspective -- tCHAPTER 10. The Altruistic Perspective: Perceptions of a Shared Humanity -- tCHAPTER 11. Perspective and Ethical Political Acts: Initial Thoughts -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs all human behavior based on self-interest? Many social and biological theories would argue so, but such a perspective does not explain the many truly heroic acts committed by people willing to risk their lives to help others. In The Heart of Altruism, Kristen Renwick Monroe boldly lays the groundwork for a social theory receptive to altruism by examining the experiences described by altruists themselves: from Otto, a German businessman who rescued over a hundred Jews in Nazi Germany, to Lucille, a newspaper poetry editor, who, armed with her cane, saved a young girl who was being raped. Monroe's honest and moving interviews with these little-known heroes enable her to explore the causes of altruism and the differences between altruists and other people. By delineating an overarching perspective of humanity shared by altruists, Monroe demonstrates how social theories may begin to account for altruism and debunks the notions of scientific inevitability that stem from an overemphasis on self-interest. As Monroe has discovered, the financial and religious backgrounds of altruists vary greatly--as do their views on issues such as welfare, civil rights, and morality. Altruists do, however, share a certain way of looking at the world: where the rest of us see a stranger, altruists see a fellow human being. It is this perspective that many social theories overlook. Monroe restores altruism to a general theory of ethical political behavior. She argues that to understand what makes one person act out of concern for others and not the self, we need to ask how that individual's perspective sets the range of options he or she finds available.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAltruism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082192140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400821921423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400821921.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999